\begin_layout Title
On Borel–Cantelli Lemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Borel–Cantelli lemma is a theorem about sequences of events.
 It is named after Émile Borel and Francesco Paolo Cantelli (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "E. Borel, 1909,F.P. Cantelli, 1917"

\end_inset

).
 The Borel–Cantelli lemma states that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(1) If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{n=1}^{\infty}P(A_{n})<\infty$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $P\{A_{n}i.o.\}=P(\limsup A_{n})=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2) If 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}$
\end_inset

 are independent and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{n=1}^{\infty}P(A_{n})=\infty$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $P\{A_{n}i.o.\}=P(\limsup A_{n})=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper, we review some extensions of the original Borel–Cantelli
 Lemma.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Barndorff-Nielsen's paper (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Barndorff-Nielsen, 1961"

\end_inset

), a general form of the Law of the Iterated Logarithm for Maximal Order
 Statistics is established by means of a generalization of the convergence
 part of the Borel-Cantelli lemmas.
 The generalized Lemma is as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Lemma:
\series default
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\liminf_{n\to\infty}P(A_{n})=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}P(A_{n}\cap A_{n+1}^{c})<\infty$
\end_inset

, then one has 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\limsup A_{n})=0.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proof: Set 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{n}=A_{n}\cap A_{n+1}^{c}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\limsup A_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F=\limsup A_{n}^{c}$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\limsup B_{n})\leq P(F^{c})=P(\liminf A_{n})\leq\liminf_{n\to\infty}P(A_{n})$
\end_inset

=0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $E\cap F\subset\limsup B_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, fix 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in E$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists m\geq n$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in A_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Put 
\begin_inset Formula $l=inf\{k\geq m:\omega\in A_{k}^{c}\};$
\end_inset

 by definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $l<\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in A_{l}\in A_{l-1}^{c}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is arbitrary, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\limsup B_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $P(E)\leq P(F^{c})+P(E\cap F)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Extended Renyi-Lamperti lemma relaxes the assumption of independence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Theorem:
\series default
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}P(A_{n})=\infty$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\liminf_{n\to\infty}\frac{\sum_{j=1}^{n}\sum_{k=}^{n}P(A_{i}\cap A_{j})}{(\sum_{j=1}^{n}P(A_{j}))^{2}}=c,$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\limsup A_{n})\geq1/c.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proof: Recall that if 
\begin_inset Formula $EX>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\epsilon<1$
\end_inset

, applying Cauchy-Schwarz inequality to 
\begin_inset Formula $E(XI\{X>\epsilon EX\})$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $P(X>\epsilon EX)\geq(1-\epsilon)^{2}(EX)^{2}/EX^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Put 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{n}=\Sigma_{j=1}^{n}I(A_{j})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{n}=\Sigma_{j=1}^{n}P(A_{j})=EJ_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Fix 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\epsilon<1$
\end_inset

 and put 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{n}=\{J_{n}\geq\epsilon s_{n}\}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{n}\to\infty$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\limsup B_{n}\subset\limsup A_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $P(B_{n})\geq(1-\epsilon)^{2}(EJ_{n})^{2}/EJ_{n}^{2}$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\limsup_{n\to\infty}P(B_{n})\geq(1-\epsilon)^{2}/c$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 is arbitrary, the proof is complete.
\end_layout

